group.colors <- c(Florida = "#00941e", NewYork ="#0034b8")

## Use the Ggplot2 package to find the following 
## graphics of the data from the two studies 
## (in each center separate): 

fl1 <- c(3,7,7,3,8,8,8,5,5,2,6,2,6,6,9,7,5,4,7,3)
ny1 <- c(8,11,9,7,8,7,8,4,13,10,6,8,12,8,6,8,5,7,7,8)
m1 = data.frame(fl1,ny1)

dep = c(fl1,ny1)
state = c(rep("Florida",20),rep("NewYork",20))
data1 = data.frame(dep,state)

m1_1 = data.frame()
fl2 <- c(13,12,17,17,20,21,16,14,13,17,12,9,12,15,16,15,13,10,11,17)
ny2 <- c(14,9,15,12,16,24,18,14,15,17,20,11,23,19,17,14,9,14,13,11)
m2 = data.frame(fl2,ny2)
dep2 = c(fl2,ny2)
data2 = data.frame(dep2,state)

library(ggplot2)

# ============== A ============== #
# =============================== #

# ======= HISTOGRAMS ======= #

ggplot(data1, aes(x=dep, fill=state, color=state)) +
  geom_histogram(position="identity", alpha=0.6,binwidth=1,boundary=-0.5)+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:13)+ labs(x = "Depression Level") + 
  labs(y = "Amount of People")+ ggtitle("Medical 1") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# In Medical Center 1, Both states had 4 people with Depression level 7.
# Florida's highest level was 9 where in NewYork the highest level was 13.
# Newyork had more than twice as many people with depression level 8. 

ggplot(data2, aes(x=dep2, fill=state, color=state)) +
  geom_histogram(position="identity", alpha=0.6,binwidth=1,boundary=-0.5)+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:24)+ labs(x = "Depression Level") + 
  labs(y = "Amount of People")+ ggtitle("Medical 2")+ 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# In Medical Center 2, It was most common for people from Florida to have a
# depression level of 17, It was most common for people from NewYork to have
# a depression level of 14.

# ======= BOXPLOTS ======= #
ggplot(data1, aes(x=dep, y=state, color=state)) +
  geom_boxplot()+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:13)+ labs(x = "Depression Level")+ 
  ggtitle("Medical 1") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# In Medical Center 1, 75% of patients from NewYork had a depression
# level 7 and above. In Florida 75% of patients had a depression level
# 7 and below. In both states the distribution 
# of depression level is Left skewed. NY has 5 outliers.

ggplot(data2, aes(x=dep2, y=state, color=state)) +
  geom_boxplot()+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:24)+ labs(x = "Depression Level")+ 
  ggtitle("Medical 2")+ 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# In Medical Center 2, the distribution of depression level in Florida is 
# approximately normal. Both states had a median level of 14.5.


# ======= DENSITY PLOTS ======= #
center = c(rep("Medical1",40),rep("Medical2",40))
dep_comb = c(c(fl1,ny1),c(fl2,ny2))
States = c(rep("Florida",20), rep("NewYork",20),
           rep("Florida",20), rep("NewYork",20))
data_comb = data.frame(dep_comb,States,center)

ggplot(data=data_comb, aes(x=dep_comb, group=center, fill=center)) +
  geom_density(alpha=.4)+ ggtitle("Medical 1 v Medical 2")+ 
  labs(x = "Depression Level")

# Distribution in Medical 2 is approximately normal.
# The distribution in Medical 1 is right skewed.

ggplot(data=data1, aes(x=dep, group=state, fill=state)) +
  geom_density(alpha=.4)+ ggtitle("Medical 1") + 
  labs(x = "Depression Level")+ 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# The greatest density of Medical 1 patients in Florida are about level 6-7.
# The greatest density of Medical 1 patients in NewYork are about level 7-9.

ggplot(data=data2, aes(x=dep2, group=state, fill=state)) +
  geom_density(alpha=.4)+ ggtitle("Medical 2") + 
  labs(x = "Depression Level")+ 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# The distribution in Medical 2 patients in Florida is 
# similar to the distribution of patients in NewYork.

# ============== B ============== #
# =============================== #

# Repeat A for 1 and 2 for each state but combining the two centers 

# ======= All Data Plots ======= #

ggplot(data_comb, aes(x=dep_comb, fill=States, color=States)) +
  geom_histogram(position="identity", alpha=0.6,binwidth=1,boundary=-0.5)+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:24)+ labs(x = "Depression Level") + 
  labs(y = "Amount of People")+ ggtitle("All Data") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+
  scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# The most common depression level is 8. Florida has some of the lowest
# depression level scores while NewYork has some of the highest scores.
ggplot(data_comb, aes(x=dep_comb, y=States, color=States)) +
  geom_boxplot()+ 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:24)+ labs(x = "Depression Level")+ 
  labs(y = "State")+ ggtitle("All Data") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=group.colors)+scale_color_manual(values=group.colors)

# NewYork has one outlier.
# Florida's overall distribution is right skewed.

# ============== C ============== #
# =============================== #

# Test the normality of depression scores for each state 
# (in each center separate). 

# ======= Normality ======= #
A1 = shapiro.test(m1$fl1)
A2 = shapiro.test(m1$ny1)
A3 = shapiro.test(m2$fl2)
A4 = shapiro.test(m2$ny2)
tab <- cbind(A1[1:2],A2[1:2],A3[1:2],A4[1:2])
colnames(tab) = c("Medical1_Fl","Medical1_NY","Medical2_Fl","Medical2_NY")
tab
##           Medical1_Fl Medical1_NY Medical2_Fl Medical2_NY
## statistic 0.9371685   0.9335806   0.9685784   0.9591607  
## p.value   0.211873    0.1809225   0.7246128   0.5272221
# The most normal distribution of scores was Medical 2 Florida.
# The least normal distribution of scores was Medical 1 NY.


# ============== D ============== #
# =============================== #

# find the numerical summaries for each medical center.

# ======= Summary Statistics ======= #
library(mosaic)
A10 = favstats(c(fl1,ny1))
A20 = favstats(c(fl2,ny2))
tab1 <- rbind(A10,A20)
rownames(tab1) = c("Medical1","Medical2")
tab1
##          min Q1 median Q3 max   mean       sd  n missing
## Medical1   2  5    7.0  8  13  6.775 2.475392 40       0
## Medical2   9 12   14.5 17  24 14.875 3.652800 40       0
# The variability of depression levels is greater in Medical Center 2.
# The mean depression level is more than twice as high in 
# Medical Center 2 than in 1.
